animal.description:
PRINCESS


Princess is a lovely 8 years old German Shepherd rescued from San Jose Animal Care by GEPDA US Rescue. She’s learned how to live inside a home, has nice manners and is housebroken. She loves people especially small children, she goes on walk once a week with her foster mom’s two years old granddaughter. She has not shown any aggression meeting dogs on walk, she might intimidate little dogs with her enthusiastic greeting and tail wagging. Per shelter, Princess met a Golden Retriever and a Frenchie and did fine with both of them. She seems to want to chase cats but leave them alone when given “leave it” commands. She knows basic commands and walks well on leash with a harness. She bonds quickly with her people, and likes to keep her people within sight. She’s doing well in foster home and now ready for adoption.


If you are interested in meeting princess please take a few moments to fill out our adoption application.

http://www.gepdaus.org/Adoption1.html

Meet Motita, a lovely black and tan  3 year old girl who's looking for a forever home. She's good with other dogs.  She LOVES to wrestle and play with other dogs. Motita is UTD on shots, spayed, microchipped, however she is heartworm positive. She has been started on slow kill heartworm treatment and will go home to her new adoptive family on this easy to give treatment provided by DFW GSR.  

Available now!
Adoption fee $350 plus tax
Fostered in Weatherford 

Interested in adopting?? Complete our adoption application today!! You can find it on our website at www.dfwgermanshepherdrescue.org

animal.description:
Blue - 6 year old Staffordshire. Needs a home with a fenced yard.

Meet Blue! This handsome fella is about 6 years old and he is just stunning!

Blue is a sweet and affectionate boy that would be quite happy being the only dog in the home. More snuggles for him!

Blue is reactive on the leash and this needs some work. His foster has been diligently working with him and a trainer and Blue is making progress. He is not suitable for places like dog parks, as it is common for his breed to be selective with other dogs they randomly meet.

In the home he is a calm boy who loves to eat, sleep like a couch potato and get cuddles. Belly rubs are his favorite! He is not a barker in the home. Blue is great with kids. The kiddos in his foster home are his buddies.

We would like to see Blue in a home with someone who is experienced with his breed and who can be an advocate for him.

He is vaccinated, chipped and neutered. His adoption fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
"If you put your mind to it, you can accomplish anything." At least, that's what my Dad said!

Hi! My name is Marty McFly and I have IVDD and even though I have NO deep pain sensation and NO nerve sensation in back legs, I HAVE LEARNED TO WALK AGAIN!!!! I do what is called "spinal walking", which is like walking based on muscle memory-- it's wobbly, but I can even RUN!!! I'm not in any pain, my foster mom is expressing my bladder several times a day, and I'm easy going about my limitations. I'm a calm, sweet dog who loves people time, cuddling, naps, and my physical therapy. I CLEARLY used to be a really active guy and I haven't let this injury stop me. I take off with the other dogs every chance I get and I don't seem to think there's anything different or wrong with me. I worked hard at getting my mobility back and it was slow going, but I had a miracle recovery because I wanted to RUN! I want to play with the other dogs, I want to snoop around! I'm bored and I want to go DO STUFF! Don't get me wrong, I've tooootally fallen in love with lounging in the big bed with my foster family... but running with other dogs is super fun. I like other dogs, love kids and babies, adult women are great, but I'm a bit picky about adult men so I might take a bit of time to accept or warm up to you.

For a couple weeks we were working with a wheelchair but I actually prefer the freedom of walking unassisted! All my bloodwork issues have completely resolved and I'm totally perfect now. I am now 100% totally normal and happy, I just have a few special circumstance that an adopter would need to consider if they want adopt me! 1. My bladder needs expressing every 4-6 hours and it's really easy 2. I need physical therapy (at home or professionally) a couple times weekly to keep me strong 3. At home TENS therapy (very inexpensive) every few days seems to make a big difference in my ability to walk 4. I walk like a drunken sailor and will always need special considerations as I can't control my back end: jumping, climbing stairs, etc.

Please don't let any of that scare you! I'm a happy, healthy, loving guy with a FANTASTIC personality. My foster mom would be happy to be involved in helping you learn how to care for me so it will be very easy! I'm really an easy guy once you get the hang of me.

Listen friends and dachshund lovers, because of you, I am walking again. Your contributions helped me get to this point and I thank you.... if you'd like to help contribute to my continuing care, click the "Sponsor This Pet" button under my picture and you can be part of my journey. Love you, Marty McFly

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!

animal.description:
Location: New Orleans, Louisiana 

Stoney was previously rescued by another rescue who does not specalize in PitBulls. They were fearful that they were going to have to euthanize Stoney and we stepped in! Stoney is approximately 5-6 months old, up to date on vaccinations, neutered & microchipped. 

Stoney is house trained, kennel trained & knows his basic commands/manners. He is an active young pup who is learning his boundaries along with socialization. His adopters must be willing to work through his obedience but allow him to be a fun loving pup also. Stoney is a sweet and playful guy who is just looking for a place to call his own. 

Interested adopters can fill out an application at canehavenrescue.com. 
Any possible questions about Stoney, please email canehavenrescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Thank you for your interest in a Home At Last Sanctuary, Inc. animal.

STOP!!! READ!! The ENTIRE DESCRIPTION before you inquire.

Do not call, email, txt, send an inquiry through any other website complete our online application FIRST.

http://hals.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=3016

Visit our official website(s) here HomeAtLastSanctuary.ORG or HALS.RescueGroups.ORG There is a complete our application only.

WE WILL ONLY BE PLACING LOLLY WITHIN A ONE HOUR DRIVE FROM ROCKVILLE MD.

OWNERSHIP EXPERIENCE WITH BULLY BREEDS PREFERRED. LOLLY WILL NOT BE PLACED IN A HOME THAT HAS BREED RESTRICTIONS.

Age: 6 Years old, Weight: 90lbs, Female, Spayed, blue nosed pitbull that is friendly, loving, and gentle to describe her core personality. She just wants to cuddle with her friends and family while receiving the occasional scratches. She loves to eat and will become a personal mop for any food that falls on the floor. When around other dogs and people Lolly is very submissive and has never bitten or caused any problems. She is just a sweet gentle dog in need of a new home. She use to be on of 6 pets 5 dogs and one cat. She got along with all, there were 2 big dogs and 2 small dogs and a medium size cats and she never got into any problems with them. She loves small children but she usually scares them away with her incessant sniffing and licking. Lolly is a lovely dog who just wants to be hugged, scratched, and loved. she is very sweet and wants attention 24/7 if she sees you just sitting there not doing anything she will come up to you and lay her head on your lap for some scratches. , she loves food more than anything, any type of food. she wants to be near you at all times and she gets along with everyone. she has no problem with other dogs and people. she has a particular interest in small things ( not in a bad way) whenever she sees small children or a hamster for example she sniffs and licks in an attempt to show interest and love but ends up scaring them away ( she means no harm and has never attempted to bite small people or small creatures she just has a thing for small creatures.)

Click here to apply to ADOPT ME

Dogs listed here come from different sources Some dog's owner have passed and their family could not care for their companion, some lifestyle has changed and a new home would be in the best interest of their companion. Some are foster dogs placed in our care by different rescue groups. Each dog may have a different process for adopting animals and charge different adoption fees.

Use the link below to complete a Short Form with your basic information.

http://hals.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=3016

Please complete the Application Short Form (link above) Your information will be reviewed and you will be advised the next step. If the dog you applied for is a match based on this information you will asked to provide Additional Information or directed to complete the Adoption Application from the Rescue Group that has placed the companion in our care.

You may be called by a volunteer, you may receive an email asking additional information or you may be requested to complete and Additional Information form. Please look our emails for further information. We are all volunteers so we will get to you as soon as we can.

We place dogs within a one hour drive from Rockville MD. we concentrate our adoptions in these areas only. With our limited resources, applications outside of our immediate service area will not be accepted, no exceptions. We take all animals to the home visit and meet and greet before they are adopted.

Thank you...

12/6/20 8:25 PM

animal.description:
Farm or large outdoor space required.....do not contact unless you have experience with large breed dogs, fenced area and a large yard or farm for him to roam. We are searching for the right home for Cooper, we want him to live happily for his life somewhere that he can roam. NO OUT OF STATE ADOPTIONS AT THIS TIME.

Cooper is a 16 month old gray and white mixed breed Kormordor/Old English Sheep dog.  He is extremely large and playful. A fenced yard is a must. He requires training, as he has not had any. He has fur that grows long so regular grooming is necessary. He requires a home where he is exercised regularly. A home without small children is required. He is very large and will jump on people until trained, so caution is recommended. Cooper is a loud barker and cannot be in a neighborhood where he is a nuisance. This is why a farm is recommended. No apartments, no condos, no neighborhood with homes close together.  
Things to keep in mind with Cooper:
*large hearding breeds
*He requires some training as he still has some puppy tendencies... Only 16mths old
*Roam-maybe Exercise is 
*Would be good with "public" farm (like pumpkin patch or farm stand ect..)
*He is very large weighing 115lbs and standing 5.5ft on his hind legs.. 
*Good with farm animals and some dogs as long as they are up for large active playmate
*Nuisance-wake the neighbor's lol

For more information call the shelter at (401) 294-2754 or email at animalshelter@exeterri.gov 

DO NOT APPLY ONLINE, please apply in person at the shelter. Adoption fee $75

Follow us on Facebook, search Friends of the Exeter Animal

animal.description:
This sweetie pie is McEntire! This darling girl was picked up as a stray with her mom Reba, and she is hoping to find a loving family in time for the holidays and the new year. Still very much a puppy, McEntire is playful and enjoys running around with her foster siblings or entertaining herself with different toys. She does love a good chewing session when it is down time, so she would like to have a large selection of chews for her to munch on instead of other inappropriate objects. This young pooch will do anything for attention, making her the pyrfect training pal. She has the sweetest personality and gets along well with everyone. McEntire is used to having playmates around, so it will be great if she can have a sibling to keep her company and help her settle down in a new environment. This young girl will thrive in a household where her people will commit time to engage in positive reinforcement training, and help her navigate the rules of the human world as she matures. McEntire was shaved due to matting, but her coat is soon to grow in beautifully. We are positive that this girl will mature into the most pyrfect companion in no time!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Blair – Black Mouth Cur mix – 2yrs. – female (46 lbs)

Introducing our beautiful girl, Blair! Blair and her sister were turned into a county shelter when their family moved. It’s so sad when the dogs aren’t considered part of the family and allowed to go along. Her sister was adopted from that shelter, but Blair sat waiting to be noticed. Well, we sure noticed her and snatched her right up! Now she’s hanging with us and having a good time until her forever family comes along. Blair is pure sweetness! She can be a bit wary of new things, but warms up quickly. She’s easygoing and loves attention, but has obviously not been exposed to much as new things seem to scare her a little and she looks for reassurance. Blair appears to be housebroken and is very polite. She loves to go for walks and does well, but will hesitate with loud noises. Her ideal home would be with another dog that is confident enough to teach her that she is safe. Blair is loving, affectionate, and great company. She will make a great hiking buddy and will snuggle close on the sofa to watch a good game. If your family is missing a good snuggler, you may want to meet our Blair. Start the process by filling out an application today.

https://form.jotform.com/91891552799173

animal.description:
This dog is part of our shelter outreach program where we take dogs from overcrowded shelters in hopes of finding them a forever home here! We generally do not have much background info on them and cannot guarantee they are housebroken. They are all up to date on vaccines, spayed/neutered and microchipped.
7 1/2 years old. 45lbs. JJ made his way up to us from TN where he was pulled from an overcrowded shelter. Poor boy was heartworm positive so he was treated by the rescue down South. His poor teeth are so worn down, he may have lived his life outside on a chain chewing rocks. He was in such bad shape and suffered major hair loss. After many medicated baths and a good diet his fur has grown in nicely. JJ keeps his kennel quite clean and does potty when taken outside. He loves his walks with volunteers and staff and walks pretty well on the leash. JJ is a special boy who needs a kind, patient soul after the rough life he has had. He loves to play with his toys and play fetch. Once he gets to know you, you will have a loyal friend for life. Likes to cuddle too. Breed experience would be great and an adult only home preferred. If interested, please fill out an online application on our website www.jerseyshoreanimalcenter.org*Per JSAC policy, puppies and kittens under 6 months will not be adopted to families with children under the age of 6 years.

animal.description:
Howdy, I'm Beau. I'm a veeery nervous pup searchin fur someone to show me the world ain't such a spooky place. I've got a purple dot cause I'm so darn scared here at the shelter, so I gotta go to a home with an experienced dog owner, and no kiddos! Right now, I'm on a medication called Fluoxetine to help with my anxiety, and it helps me a lot, but a calm environment is going to be super important to help me feel at home. I don't mind taking my meds though, I eat them right up with a good snack to wash it down! I'm nervous around other dogs, but I don't mind the company of a calm cat. My foster tells me I'm a real good boy; I'm totally housebroken and I don't need to be crated at night! I don't enjoy car rides very much, but I'm still on my best behavior when we're out for a drive. I'm not exactly what you'd call a social butterfly, but if you could take me home and show me a little love, I'd be ever so grateful!

I'm in an Ambassador foster home! I'm not at the shelter, so please call to set up a meet and greet appointment. You can talk directly with my foster parent to know exactly what I'm like in a home. 

What's HW+? I've completed the treatment for heartworms, I'll just need to keep a calm lifestyle for a little while longer. Please don't be deterred, my lifespan isn't shortened, and I'm not contagious to your other pets.

Take me on a Slumber Party! You can bring me home for a 3 day - 30 day trial period. HSSC will provide food, medications, and necessities. If I'm not the one for you, just bring me back to HSSC and provide feedback on what would be the best home for me.

animal.description:
Clyfe is about 6 years old, has a cleft palette, and is heartworm positive. Because of this, he has been sitting in a shelter in Texas, waiting for someone to see past his flaws for the past 2 months. He has the sweetest disposition and huge eyes that he uses to get all the love from the shelter staff. He is very calm and so so sweet!

Clyfe made a doggy friend or two while at the shelter, but preferred to roam and get booty scratches rather than play. He is very calm and clean while in his kennel and perhaps that hurt his chances for adoption at the shelter. Sadly, if you don't stand out, you don't stand a chance.

But Clyfe has now been rescued by NorthStar Pet Rescue so he is safe and loved. He is being treated for heartworm in Texas and he will not be coming to New Jersey until late February/early March. Although Clyfe is fine with dogs outside of the house he cannot live with another dog.

If you are interested in meeting Clyfe when he arrives and giving this guy all the love he's been missing, please fill out an adoption form at www.northstarpets.org & ask for CLYFE TX!

animal.description:
NOTE: The mailbox petfinder sends the "Ask About" email inquiries to is not as closely monitored as the email address applications go to. That feature is a default with petfinder, and is not a part of our adoption process.

The first step in our adoption process is the application. Completed applications take priority over inquiries. To apply to adopt, please copy and paste the following url:

https://fs30.formsite.com/legacygsd/form4/index.html

Introducing Willis! Willis is a lab mix. He weighs about 65lbs and is around 5 yrs old.

Willis was at a small shelter in MS. They put out a plea for their medical cases and we just had to scoop up this cutie patootie! Willis had heartworms. Heartworms are an epidemic in the south. It is a process to get treated but Willis did great! He is completely recovered and is ready for his forever home!
Willis is a goofy boy. He loves to play and be silly. He enjoys playing with other dogs and Doing zoomies is one of his favorite activities. He loves to chase balls but doesn't really get the concept of fetching and retrieve. He is currently being fostered in a home with young children, other dogs and a cat and he does great with all. He is crate/kennel trained. He is learning his house manners and is doing well. We recommend kenneling him when he will be unsupervised. This is the routine he is used to and he can't get puppy mischief while he is tucked away in his "house".

Willis is fully vetted, up to date on vaccines, sailed through heartworm treatment, is neutered and microchipped and is one monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention.

As with all of our dogs, we recommend a basic obedience class to help him understand what is expected of him, and this also helps with the bonding process.

Willis's adoption fee is $475, which covers all his vetting, preventatives, fostering costs and other associated expenses. We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21.

animal.description: Little One is approx. 11 years old but still young at heart and very active. After 2.5 months in his foster home and relearning to trust people again, he has really become a sweetie pie! He's very loving, loyal, funny, and gentle! He spins and dances on his hind legs every time you take him out for a walk. He lavishes you with kisses and begs for butt scratches... yes he LOVES butt scratches! LOL! He is always right next to you wherever you are... waiting for attention, pets, and scratches. He instantly loves all men - even huge 6'6"" men!! He still hesitates before you pick him up but he relaxes really quickly and settles into your arms. He is comfortable at home by himself now. He'll bark for the first 2 minutes and then settle into his bed and patiently wait for you to come home. He takes treats from you very gently and appreciate you putting a jacket on him when he's cold... he'll give you more kisses to show appreciation. He also now plays with the other foster dogs and walks around wagging his tail in confidence. He hardly marks in the house anymore and has learned that people do love him and won't hurt him.

animal.description:
Hey im Harry the hound, I am about a year old and am about 80 lbs. They think I am some sort of a hound mix. My foster mom thinks I am as handsome as Harry Styles and could make a great impression on everyone you take me to meet! I am extremely sociable as I love other people and other dogs. I tend to be more submissive, as even one of our volunteer's small dog barked at me, and I knew they were the boss. I am looking for a family to call my own, one where I could possibly even run around the yard as my family hangs out outside, and if there is barbecue that would be a plus! I'd love to have a bite or 2! Once I get my energy out, I am very relaxed in the house. I just lie and flop right around. I am crate and house trained, so leaving me at home when you need to go run an errand is totally cool with me! If you are interested in meeting me, reach out to my foster mom Liz at 214-616-6128, and she can tell you how much she adores me and thinks I am awesome 

Harry is heartworm tested, neutered, as well as up to date on vaccines and even microchipped! If you are interested in adopting him, fill out an application at https://shelter2rescue.org/DogAdoption.html

animal.description: At first glance, it might appear that Monty is channeling his inner Eeyore. With those soulful puppy dog eyes and that prominent underbite, he has a way of pulling at our heartstrings. But don't be fooled! This fun-loving boy is all wiggles and tail wags when he's playing with toys or exploring the great outdoors. If you're looking for the perfect trail companion, Monty is your boy. He goes out on the trail on a regular basis, and can run for miles. Bikers, strollers, dogs, cranky swans and other distractions don't faze him in the slightest. If that face isn't enough to convince you to take him home immediately, we should also note that he has received rave reviews in his foster home and on sleepovers with volunteers. He's fully house-trained and has proven to be a respectful houseguest. He's also an excellent snoozer and is content to chill on the couch and keep you company for hours during Netflix marathons. In addition to being a top-notch lounger and trail companion, Monty is also in the Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. This smart pup recently became TOP Dog Ready, which means he has already learned all the skills in his training plan, including walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers, calmly walking past another dog, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' and coming when called. And as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with Monty after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 If you're looking for an athletic, sweet-natured and handsome pup, why not go the full Monty? Follow Monty on Instagram @ adopt_montythepit https://www.instagram.com/adopt_montythepit/?hl=en

Please contact Linda for more information about this pet.We welcomed Chewy to rescue just shy of 2 weeks ago. You can never be sure what a dog will be like but watching his videos you could see a chubby happy people kind of dog who was not limping or showing anything more than a happy black dog. As predicted this is who Chewy is!! On his first day in rescue he came in to meet his foster family and immediately decided he was going to be happy while he was here. We are learning more about him and all is good so far!!! He is a bit fearful of large dogs but is fostered with smallish female terrier and they are GOOD buddies.
Chewy just needs his microchip and will be going home for his first Christmas in his new family home!!!

Come see this pup on Saturdays during adoption event hours. Please email Linda at lbredfire@sbcglobal.net or call WT&F's Dog Team voicemail 707-812-9030 to get a jump on the process, ask questions, and/or to confirm they will be there. Dog adoptions are held outside Napa Petco every Saturday - 12:30pm to 4:00pm.
This dog comes spayed/neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested negative, and more with an adoption fee/donation to Whiskers, Tails and Ferals in Napa, CA. See more information at http://whiskerstailsandferals.org/.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Interested in adopting? See our adoption proccess.
BETTY is a big red-headed beauty that absolutely loves attention! As soon as you start petting her, she leans in and rolls down your legs to get on her back to ensure she gets that belly rubbed! She is well-mannered and walks well on leash, which is good since she weighs 100 pounds! She knows some commands including sit/stay, shake, and down and will happily do them until she is on a leash - then it is all about her exploring and walking. She will enjoy short regular walks to build up her stamina. She was uninterested in a couple other dogs introduced to her, even when they were sniffing and trying to engage. With that she may do well with another dog in the home, but would likely not mind being your one and only! Betty came into a local shelter as a stray so we don't know a lot about her but we do know she is gentle, sweet, happy, and is deserving of a home of her very own where she can be pampered! Interested in sponsoring? See our sponsorship information.

Finn is a 2 year-old Beagle mix that was found wandering the streets.  He had been let down by humans and didn't trust anyone enough to catch him.  A team of volunteers ended up trapping him and bringing him to safety at PAWS Tinley Park.  He is scared of leashes and slow to trust new people.  But, when he learns you're OK, he is so loving and loyal!  Finn likes to lean against his people to know he is safe.  Finn will make a wonderful companion for a patient and calm person.  He gets along with other dogs, but would do best without children or an active household.  We can't wait to watch this sweetie blossom!


*We are closed to the public for viewing. Please email adoptions@pawstinleypark.org if you are interested in adopting.

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please visit our website to check on their current availability: http://www.pawstinleypark.org.. Adoptions are limited to 50 miles from the shelter. We do not ship animals. Adoption fees for dogs are $125-$275 based on age. While we do our best, we cannot make guarantees on breed, exact age and house training of our dogs. Peoples Animal Welfare Society (P.A.W.S.) of Tinley Park, IL is a no-kill non-profit 501(c) (3) organization.

Phone: 815-464-7298

animal.description:
{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name:Tahiti
Size: ~Medium range: 26-60 lbs
Adoption Donation:$75 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Spayed Female, Vaccinations current, Microchip, No other pets, No children, and must have a fenced-in yard

Tahitiis a very sweet dog!

Foster Home Feedback

*
Tahitineeds a home with No other pets, No children, and must have a fenced-in yard

1/9/21 Volunteer Feedback: Tahiti is a very special dog and we love spending time with her. Since Thanksgiving, Tahiti has been a regular visitor to our home several times a week. She is so loving and wiggles with emotion. Tahiti is a people-person dog, she immediately liked my wife and son. She also meets strangers well (such as neighbors and other family members that stop by). She does not react or bark when the doorbell rings - quite different from our previous dogs! She loves back rubs especially after she's been playing hard.

Tahiti is reactive toward other dogs but has shown a lot of improvement over the past months. If we are walking down a sidewalk and a dog is barking at her from inside a house - she shows no concern. If a dog is barking from a fenced area, she will look but redirects easily. If a dog is walking on the same path toward you she will throat growl. At that time, we turn around or turn down another street. She will redirect well. Yesterday we had two surprises on our walks: the first one coming to a blind corner and meeting up with another dog about 25 feet away. It surprised both Tahiti and me! I said come and we walked quickly across the street. Tahiti didn't bark or growl. She just moved alongside me. I was so proud of her! The second was a dog turning onto the street we were on about 40 feet away. We just turned around and walked in the opposite direction. Again, she did not react with growls or barks. She did look back occasionally but would look to me when she did! So proud again!!! This morning I let her out in our backyard. Our neighbor's reactive dog heard us and immediately began barking, Tahiti turned around and ran back in the house! I couldn't believe it! So proud of this girl!!!

Tahiti is a great dog, and once you learn her cues it's pretty easy to understand what she wants. She needs her nap time and will kennel and sleep easily. She needs low stimulation- one toy at a time, and a back rub when you're done playing is her cue that we're done. She likes to watch you vacuum or prepare dinner. Tahiti likes to lay on the couch while you watch tv - but doesn't sleep (so that doesn't count as nap time). When she's overtired, she will force herself to go-go-go, like a toddler. When she gets like that she's almost relieved to go into her kennel and sleep.

She is completely house trained and knows her basic commands. She loves the kennel and the quiet security it provides for her to rest. Tahiti loves balls and stuffed animals and Bully sticks.

I believe Tahiti will be a great addition to your home, and she really deserves a place to call her forever home. She is a good girl who shows her love for human contact through kisses and plopping her body down on your lap. I think a home without children would be ideal and she needs to be the only dog (pet) in the house as well.

1/2/21 Volunteer Feedback: The two most scientifically accurate words to describe Tahiti: Squishy Wigglebutt! I LOVE THIS GIRL! She is so loving and sweet and wow is she smart! She really catches on fast - maybe more than any foster I've had. She understands commands quickly and thrives in an environment with a schedule. Tahiti knows what time it is and what to expect. You say "kennel" or "nap time" and she runs to the kennel and waits for her treat before laying down for a nap or to go to bed. She sleeps in her kennel as we realized that she has trouble turning off her brain to really rest at night and during naps. Without the downtime she kind of turns into a "cranky toddler" - that's the best way to describe it as she's just overtired and doesn't know why. But really she's a 90% completely awesome dog and maybe 3% cranky toddler (with 7% somewhere in the "I can tell it's time for a nap" phase). Don't let that scare you off - I really think she'll outgrow it as she matures.

As mentioned she would do best with a schedule and continued training to reduce her pulling when walking (she just gets so excited). With some consistency, and as she just catches on so quickly to positive re-enforcement training, I think she'd do amazing if someone continued working with her.
She can get bored if she doesn't get a walk or two (or a couple of games of fetch in) during the day. She hasn't been destructive and has had no accidents, she goes to the door when she has to go outside. We are working on Tahiti learning to self-soothe and to go grab a bone or something to chew on when she's overstimulated, but she is still young and just needs some direction and patience.

Tahiti's a champion snuggler who is ALWAYS EXCITED to see people! She loves walks and playing fetch and listens pretty well, given she's still a youngster.

Whoever gets Tahiti will be one VERY LUCKY FAMILY!

11/24/2020 Volunteer Feedback: Hanging out with Tahiti (aka the dog of a million kisses) for the Thanksgiving break. Tahiti is probably the most affectionate dog I have ever met. She loves her people!

We've been on a couple of walks and she did great ignoring garbage trucks and people. She is house trained and will go potty outside on command. She loves to play fetch and did well giving back the ball by the end! And she absolutely loved her green squishy ball!

11/23/2020 Volunteer Feedback: Each and every day, us volunteers get to learn a little bit more about Tahiti as she starts to come out of her shell. This little wild child loves to go, go, go! We enjoyed some time out and about this morning and chilled in a home setting. She was very excited to be there and wanted to make sure she was a part of everything.

Riding in the car made her a little anxious, but with the help of some cheese (and a good doggy seatbelt) we made the ride a success. We ducked into Petco for a little bit too, and she enjoyed all the smells that they had to offer. She got a little grumbly when another dog was barking at her a lot, but she redirected easily and was much more interested in treats. She LOVES people, of all shapes and sizes. She wanted to make friends with every person, a little social butterfly!

11/21/2020 Volunteer Feedback: Tahiti is absolutely the people's dog. She is sweet as pie and will give you enough love that having another pet won't even cross your mind. She wants to be your one and only, the princess in her very own castle! And oh, does she deserve it.

While she may not like other animals, Tahiti makes up for it tenfold in all of her qualities. She has a zest for life that just can't be ignored! She loves every single person she meets and everything she does is done with a wagging tail and wiggling butt. She loves to give kisses and be close to her people. Tahiti adores toys and carries them around with her like they are the greatest prize she has ever received.

While she may not want to live with other dogs, she isn't reactive on walks. She gives them quiet indifference when passing by and doesn't give them a care in the world. Tahiti does need a little work on her basic manners, but luckily she is very treat-motivated and a quick study! She doesn't ever make a mess in her kennel, but she does get a little sad to be left by herself.

I think she would love a family who wants to be active as Tahiti has a lot of energy and wants to get as much out of the day as she can! She is just an absolute love and is sure to be the perfect 4-legged addition to your family.To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
I’m about 12 years old and weigh 18 lbs and everyone says I am a pretty sweet boy. I love to take naps and am very happy to be on my bed in my crate or laying outside in a sunny spot on the deck. I also love to snuggle on the sofa and get my head scratched and petted. My foster mommy is amazed that I have never had an accident in the house. She says I have perfect potty manners and I know how to go to the back door and ask to go out when I need to.

There are other dogs here and to be honest I would prefer to have my person all to myself, even though I try to ignore them and we all get along. There is also a cat here and I hardly turn my head to look at her when she is eating my food while I sit right there.

I was in bad shape when I came to live here, I was in pain and very scared because I didn’t understand why I was taken to the shelter before being rescued by Tzu Zoo. I was overweight and that made my joints hurt a lot, on top of that my tail was amputated due to a tumor. One of my achilles tendons is ruptured so I walk funny, but I can still get to where I need to get. I have lost a couple of pounds (could probably lose a couple more) and my tail has healed and I feel so much better now. I have dry eye and will need drops in my eyes for the rest of my life, they feel so much better now that I have my medicine.

I would be happiest with an experienced dog owner who just wants to love me and take care of me, and I will love them back. I’m looking for an angel.

Please apply at tzuzoorescue.com if you are interested in adopting from Tzu Zoo Rescue.  More information available by contacting tzradopt@gmail.com.

[NOTE: We are a rescue NOT a shelter, meaning WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY THAT OPENS TO THE PUBLIC. Typically, an application and home visit (both of which are required for adoption) MUST be completed, BEFORE a potential adopter will be introduced to one of our pets, in order to first determine that our basic adoption requirements are met, prior to introductions being made. We also utilize personal reference and vet checks (to ensure that any pets already in the potential adoptive home are current on vaccines, heart worm prevention and sterilized) in our adoption process, all of which is intended to ensure that the best match, between pet and people, is made. The adoption fee is based on on the dog's age.

Vlad is an 8-year-old, 75lb, chow/lab mix.  He's real love.  One of the volunteer favorites.

Vlad needs one confident owner, structure, and routine.  He has been in rescue for over 3 years waiting for that perfect combination of adult owners with protection breed experience and someone who wants to love an older dog. + open space for him to roam. Vlad has some guarding behavior..

No kids for Vlad. He needs a quiet household to live his golden years.  He's good with smaller dogs and has previously lived with cats.  He does great on a leash and doesn't seem to pay attention to dogs his size on a leash.

Vlad loves to go on walks. He's pretty independent like most chows.  Like treats but gets bored standing around.  He likes to be resting or on the go!  He's got a great personality.

Vlad is a big dog and needs a detached home.  A yard would be great but not required.

Vlad is neutered, UTD on vaccinations, and micro-chipped.  His adoption fee is $100.

Stella is a 4-5 year old Lab/Pit mix. She is loving, friendly and wants nothing more than to have a home where she can get lots of cuddles, treats and attention. Once she knows you she is sweet as a button and loves her people deeply.

Stella's favorite things are treats, a comfy bed and lots of pets. You can find her cuddled up on her bed and sunbathing on a nice day. She has a calm demeanor and walks well on a leash, though she can get distracted if she spots a critter!

Stella came to us from Texas where she was found as a stray.  She is roughly 45lbs and can not be with other pets. 

Stella would do best in an adult only home or with kids over the age of 12. Not because she is aggressive towards people, she just prefers a quiet and calm home where she can be loved and spend her days relaxing :)

She is UTD on her vaccinations, spayed and micro-chipped.  Her adoption fee is $300.

animal.description:
Kace is a Great Pyrenees mix who was found dumped in the country in Missouri with his three littermates. A young lady who rescues animals found them and contacted us to find them good homes. Kace's siblings have all been adopted. He is still waiting for his Furever home!

Looking for a new best bud? Look no further, Kace is your guy. Kace is a very smart, sweet, loyal pup who will want to always be by your side, no matter if you are taking a nap or playing in the yard. He loves snuggles and pets and is happy to meet new people, large or small. Kace does great on a leash and loves going for long walks or runs on the trail. He is doing well with house training and will try to let you know by circling the door when he needs to go out. Kace enjoys being around other dogs and is playfully friendly with the cats in his foster home. He seems to understand he needs to be gentle with his Pyr Paw. He is a little nervous about walking on linoleum flooring, but can be coaxed into it. For a Great Pyrenees, he is on the quiet side and not a big barker. Kace will come to you neutered, up to date on vaccinations, up to date on flea/tick preventives, and microchipped. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved you must pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Kace can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. We are able to transport Kace to those states. If you would like to give Kace a furever home, please fill out an application on our website. 

Being fostered in Columbia, MO

animal.description:
Juri is 1-2 years old and 28lbs

Hi, I'm Juri! I recently had 7 beautiful pups but now I get to focus on ME! I'm the sweetest girl who loves to get pets and will paw at you for more attention. I love to go for long walks and get so excited when you grab my leash. I also like to hang out and snuggle on the couch. I know to potty outside and am a good sleeper at night. I'm good with sleeping in my crate or in my own bed in your room. I seem to be a little unsure about new men, I will sometimes growl when meeting someone new, but I warm up quickly.

Medical notes: I am heartworm and ehrlichia positive. I will start my 28 day antibiotics before my heartworm treatment. You can adopt me before my treatment, but if you do - the cost associated would be your responsibility. Please check with your vet on pricing. https://www.heartwormsociety.org/

You can still come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2.  On Saturday's from 2-4pm, the events are open to the public. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

Ben is a really sweet boy who bonds deeply to his people and is very loyal. He needs room to roam and play and is best suited for country life or in a rural area. He is not an apartment or city dog. He would love nothing more than to take long walks with his owner and then cuddle up inside on a warm bed. 

Ben LOVES treats and would enjoy lounging around the house with a nice bone. He would also thrive in obedience training as he is smart and has a desire to please his people.

Ben requires a large breed experienced home with a securely fenced yard, somewhere rural. No other pets in the home, preferably an adult only home but he could be okay with kids 12 and older with evaluation.

Ben's adoption fee is $200, he is up to date on shots, neutered and micro-chipped.

Zeppelin is a 2 year old pitty mix. He is a very sweet boy! Zeppelin gets along with almost everything he meets: dogs, cats, kids! He is a laid back dog who just wants a family of his own. Zeppelin comes from a home where there were many other dogs, and he would get picked on by the other dogs. He doesn't let his past affect him though! Zeppelin is very sweet natured. This good boy would love to find his furever home!



The Junior Humane Society is a non-profit, all volunteer, animal rescue group. For over 30 years, we have helped animals in the Gulf Coast area. 
All animals waiting for adoption are placed in foster homes. Before placing the animal in a furever home, JHS provides all necessary vet care, including but not limited to: shots, spaying, and neutering. 
We hold adoptions event every Saturday at PetSmart in Pensacola, FL from 12-4

***APPLICATION PROCESS CAN TAKE UP TO ONE WEEK - HOME AND FENCE CHECK AND VET RECORDS ARE REQUIRED!***

MEET SUZIE!!!

Suzie is 12yrs old and an absolute sweetheart!! Suzie weighs about 8lbs!!

Suzie has had a crappy life. Sadly, her owners never gave her the vet care she deserved. She was underweight and also flea infested with hair missing from insistent scratching to the point of bleeding. .

 Suzie has now been spayed and up to date on vaccinations, had a dental and ready for a new life!!

She has recovered nicely and her hair has grown back and she has finally got the vet care she deserved!

Suzie is a friendly, energetic and happy girl that gets along well with other dogs!

Suzie would do best with someone home a lot as she is a velcro dog and loves to be with her people. She gets along great with other dogs and is submissive dog. 

Want to meet this little gem?

EMAIL:
mini-mutts@outlook.com

**************************************
*NO LARGE DOGS
*NO CHILDREN UNDER 5 YRS OLD
NO APARTMENTS

*************************************
TO APPLY-Your dog’s heartworm prevention and testing must be seen on vet records or other proof must be included. The records must show 2 years of continuous prevention on current dogs.

Your application will NOT be approved without this documentation.

***If no previous dog history we require the purchase of one year supply of heartworm prevention. (cost $40) added onto adoption fee. ***

animal.description:
Meet Angel! Angel is a beautiful, 7-year-old, Treeing Walker Coonhound. She is great with people and kids. She does not look or act her age and is a rambunctious coonhound and full of energy. Shemost enjoys playing ball and has a hoard of tennis balls that she will happily bring to you. Angel has lived with a very loving family since she was 10 months old but since her family has grown in size, her owners are no longer able to spend the time with her that she needs to run and play. Angel benefits from lots of exercise. A large backyard or space with a secure fence where she can run to her hearts content would be ideal. She can be anxious at times, especially in new environments, but does very well with anxiety medication to keep her calm. Angel has good manners inside the home and doesn't jump on furniture. She enjoys napping and sleeping in her plush, soft dog bed. Angel loves to interact with people and children and is very gentle even with babies and little ones. She loves to be petted and scratched behind her big, floppy ears and always appreciates a nice belly rub. She also loves to give you her paw, sit, and lay down for a delicious treat. Angel has lived with another dog in her home since she was a puppy, and they happily sleep and play together but she can be reactive towards other dogs. She can be slowly introduced to other dogs with help from a professional trainer and while on medication but a single dog household with no cats would be best for Angel. All she needs is someone who wants to play with her and give her pets and she will be your most loyal companion! She would also be a great hiking buddy if you have alot of land.
Age: 7years
Weight: 75 lbs
Vetting: spayed, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative

animal.description: Greetings!  My name is Beth (HWTH#20251A).  I am a Belgian Shepherd mix, born on 5/19/2019, and I weigh 59 lbs.  I came to Halfway to Home after I was found as a stray dragging my leash in Lake Los Angeles.  My people did not claim me so I am ready for a new forever home!  The nice people at Halfway to Home are just getting to know me.  I am a very friendly girl.   Belgian Shepherds are similar in personality and behavior to German Shepherds.  We require a combination of lots of physical activity, mental stimulation, and socialization to be happy.  I need a large tall-fenced yard (not chain-link because I am a climber) for play and at least 2 longs walks a day. Other outdoor activities such as jogging or hiking would be a bonus!   Obedience training is essential to channel my mental energy in a productive way and make sure I behave appropriately.   I have not had much training yet so my new owner needs to be patient and disciplined to help me become the loyal and trusting companion that you want me to be. I love to be around people so I need to be included as part of the family.  I do not know yet how well I would do with children, other dogs or cats.  I shed a lot, and regular brushing is important to keep my skin and coat healthy.   So what do you think, would you like to meet me?  If you would like more information about me, please call Sandy at 661-824-4495 (it is a landline phone).  I look forward to seeing you soon!!

animal.description:
To make a family perfect, on Showtime or beyond!

Hullo hullo! My name is Ian and I am the good-looker from the 'Shameless' crew rescued from Mexico! I am a lil pupper, all of 7 months old and a German Shepherd mix. I have been a good boi at my foster home and learning good bathroom habits. I am fully house and leash trained. Not to brag, I am a smartie and getting hang of some commands! I have been fixed!

I recently was diagnosed with megaesophagus. It's not a biggie, but I need to eat in an upright/seated position because my esophagus doesn't work properly, and I need one medicine for life. I readily take my meds with a cheesy snack. I have been feeding from a raised platform by myself now and I have been doing good! From needing to be fed by hands, I have moved on to eat like a good boy from the platform. As long as I take my prescribed medicines regularly, I am all good!

Like the broody teen on the show, I am figuring life out. but I pepper it with a bunch of curiosity. I was on the shy side when I come across new people, and kids, but I am growing up to be a friendly guy, with all the politeness of a perfect doggo. Also, I love to play and that definitely helps! I now know the magic of Kong toys and playing tug on rope toys. Like I said earlier, I have the smarts and I have the playful energy. Once I am all done, I will snooze off by myself in my bed or the crate. I do need naps so that I am well-rested and not cranky. I may steal your spot on the couch, but I am cute to get away with it! I definitely am evolving to be more social and if the dogs and people are looking friendly, I am a happy chappy! I am pretty good with older kiddos too!

My foster fam claims that I am a super handsome, smart and independent fella and any family would be lucky to have me! I would need Puppy 101 lessons to be the best grown-up boy! As long as I have love and attention, I will be good. An experienced dog owner will certainly be great! My adoption fee is $400 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here: https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description: Wicked wants everyone to know that his name has nothing to do with his temperament, his owner was just a huge musical-theater fan. Volunteers say he's been a very sweet and social boy since coming to PACC, he enjoys running and playing in the yards and will give you his BEST sit and a paw (and be ready for that force of that paw!). Wicked is one of the biggest pupperoni's we have seen here in a while and he is wicked strong. He will need a strong person to handle him on his walks and to teach him some leash manners. Wicked has mixed notes with other dogs here at PACC and in his last home so he might be best as your one and only or would need an intro to any other pets in the house. I mean, he is a LOT of doghow much more could you need? His previous owner says he is housebroken and enjoys snoozing on the couch. Wicked is a sweet fella who just wants to get out of the shelter and into a home. Do you have some room in your home and heart for a big lovebug?

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.KALI

is an all-black 27-pound, spayed female-Italian Greyhound mix of 27 pounds.

Kali was found as a stray and no owner came forth to claim so she was scheduled to be euthanized for being too fearful in her pen. the poor girl was so frightened in that noisy, cold shelter for 10 days she was beside herself in fear. When Kali arrive, although initially frightened, she let me take her out of the crate, and in a few moments, she came and lay next to me and seemed to say Thank You for rescuing her.

Kali is very sensitive and intuitive. "She reads the room" and seems to pick up on people's emotions and intent.. Kali will need experienced, gentle, understanding adopters who will give her a little time to settle. Perhaps retired or work from home folks who will have time for her. Talking sweetly to Kali goes a long way and she can hear in your voice if you are a good person. I do not know if she is leash trained, but she is smart, and with wearing a leash and harness inside for a few days, taking her out in the yard to start and training her should be fairly easy.

Kali is on a Human grade and Raw food diet. she is approx 8 pounds overweight, so that's like 50 extra pounds on what should be a 100-pound person. She needs help to get her trimmed down for her health and longevity. Rompin Paws will educate her adopter(s) in canine and species-specific feeding.

Kali has a 595.00 adoption fee. All monies are recycled to save more dogs.

Cats receive a vaccine for Rhinotracheitis-Calici-Panleukopenia-Chlamydia Psittaci. The animals at our shelter have been picked up stray. animal.description:
Meet Maggie the marvelous! This 2 year old, brindle Cane Corso has had a rough road where she has been bounced around and not treated the best historically, but BDHP is here to make sure she finds the stability and right family who can give her her happily ever after that she deserves. While she does suffer from slight incontinence from being spayed too young, it is well managed with taking Proin 2 x day and she is completely house trained if she takes her meds. Maggie is also crate trained, leash trained and knows come, sit, shake, free, and get out. She is a typical teen who still likes to play and chew, is a big fan of tug toys and bones, but she is also game to chill and watch a good TV program to relax. True to her breed, she is leery of strangers and will require a strong leader who is familiar with the importance of rules, boundaries and management to set her up for success. She gives very clear body signals when she is uncomfortable with a situation and just needs someone who will pay attention and not push her beyond what she can handle. Once Maggie knows she can trust you she is as loving and loyal as they get! She will make a wonderful companion for a more quiet household and does fine with older kids and larger dogs overall. She does occasionally resource guard high value items, but it is easy to feed separately and save these items for when she is alone. Maggie is incredibly smart, loves walks and playtime with other dogs, and can't wait to find her forever home.

Giant Breed Experienced Homes Only.
To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

I love to run in the yard and I'm pretty fast. I like jumping up into your lap and cuddling or just sitting on the couch next to you. I'd let you pet me, too. I like dogs but sometimes go overboard so would be best as an only dog in your house. I have enough love to keep you happy! I start out shy with new people but if they give me time, treats, or loving pets, I come around. I'm not sure if I would be good with small children as I haven't been around them lately and don't remember if I did in the past. I do have a touch of arthritis in my front legs, but that is to be expected given my age. I may not be a running companion, but I'll happy zoom around our fenced in back yard!

Little Bit's adoption fee is $250 and includes his neuter, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives PLUS a free basic obedience course at Cedar Run Pet Boarding & Daycare in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, be altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives. Our adoption process includes reference and vet checks, a home visit and a background check. Please submit an adoption application at www.Adopthope.org if you would like to meet Little Bit!

animal.description:
Phantom came to THS after being transferred from another shelter! Here is what the previous shelter had to say about Phantom!

Phantom does very well in playgroups, loose and wiggly, stays to himself until other dogs greet him. 

Here at THS, Phantom was always a friendly face when our staff walked into the dog kennels. He loves nothing more than spending time with people and with dog friends! He has met multiple dogs that matched his energy level, and he had nothing but a good time with them! This special boy even knows how to sit on command! You can tell he wants to learn more skills and commands, he is always waiting for instructions! Phantom is still learning his manners and does not realize his size. Due to this, he can not go home with children under the age of 10 years old. 

Phantom has been treated for heartworm disease. THS requires all adopters of heartworm positive dogs to purchase a 1 year supply of heartworm preventative at the time of adoption.

Phantom is currently residing in foster care! So far, his foster mom has said that Phantom is learning everyday! Fetch recently became a reality and is a big help to getting some energy out! He is doing better with playing with their dogs but still plays rough, which seems to be his favorite thing. He is developing an attachment to his family and loves to snuggle. Crate training is a little difficult, but he is the best copilot when his foster mom has to run errands!

 Please email foster@toledohumane.org if interested in adopting Phantom!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.One of the best-known blockbuster franchises in the Universe - from comic books to the big screen to new forever homes in Western New York! Pixie Mamas welcomes the X-Men!

Mama Mystique was found abandoned in the street, nursing her 2-week-old puppies. Our rescue partners in Texas scooped up these undercover super heroes and handed them over to us for safe keeping. Now that her super hero children have all found their forever homes, it is Mystique's turn. Mama Mystique faced danger, hunger, pain and fear - and protected her tiny children in those unsafe streets till she was rescued. Do you have what it takes to adopt a super hero? Do you have what it takes to love one of the X-Men?

Mystique is one of the most popular - and most beautiful - of the X-Men. She has been portrayed by such gorgeous actresses as Jennifer Lawrence and Rebecca Romijn. Her power is one of transformation. She can appear as anyone, at any time to best suit her needs of the moment.

This power is shared by our Mystique. She was a valiant warrior protecting her puppies in the streets until they were all rescued. She then morphed into a loving mother, teaching them all they need in order to survive and thrive in their forever homes. Mystique is currently starring as "amazing and loving foster dog" and is looking forward to her most important role- the part of a lifetime - in her forever home.

Mystique is a 2-year-old chihuahua mix. Her fur is a thick ivory color, with rusted-rose colored angel kisses on her forehead - the exact place where you kiss your children goodnight. She has peach blush ears and one single copper raindrop at the base of her short & stubby, squared-off tail. She has very soulful eyes, you can see the tough choices she had to make and the strength it took to make them staring back at you. Mystique loves to cuddle. She will reach out with a paw and boop you on the arm if you haven't been paying enough attention to her. She does not, however, love to be picked up and carried around. She will let you lift her up & move her from one place to another - like when she takes over the entire pillow and there is no room for your head. Or when she has settled into the absolute center of the blanket, trapping you against the mattress with no wiggle room. She seems very anxious and will begin to struggle when she is tightly contained in someone's arms. She wants to be with her people, but she doesn't want to be restrained by her people.

Mystique will guard her home - and bark to warn you of anyone in the vicinity. She will make her point, then settle back. There is no random barking chorus with her, no constant yips just for attention. She will say her piece and expects her people to listen the first time. She is wary of new people - everyone has to prove themselves trustworthy with her. You earn your place in her heart. She seems to be extra cautious around meneven if you have been in the house visiting for hours, if you are a man who doesn't live there & you move to go to the bathroom or kitchen, she will bark all over again. Once she is familiar with you, it is no longer an issue and she will put her high-alert level street smarts back under cover.

Her foster mama works, so she uses potty pads during the day. It is clear she would rather potty outside, but she uses them. She has a fenced yard at her foster mom's house, but is doing well with a leash & harness. Mystique is a climber, so her fence will have to be stockade or vinyl fencing. Homes with a chain-link fence cannot be considered, as she will put her dainty little toes into those holes and be up and out of the yard in a few minutes if the spirit moved her.

She plays well with the other dogs in her foster home, but she is always first in line for cuddles - pushing her brothers & sisters out the way to be noticed and recognized. This most likely comes from the hand-to-mouth street existence she had as a single mom with mouths to feed. She does have moments of melancholy since her children have all been adopted. Like every good mother out there, the needs of the kids come first. Now that her children are all provided for, her time of struggle should be over. It is now time for her wish to come true - the dream of her own forever home.

Mystique is spayed, up to date with vaccines, microchipped, flea/worm treated and tested neg. for heartworm. Her adoption fee is $400 1/31/21 1:27 PM

animal.description:
HEATON: 1 year old, 34lbs, Lab Mix, Neutered Male NEEDS HOME OUTSIDE OF THE CITY 

Raise your hand if you could use an uplifting transformation story. So... all of you. Weird. Heaton joined us in October. He grew up in a nasty hoarding situation in rural Tennessee and barely had any human contact until he arrived in New York. Horns, cement, leashes, hands it was almost too much for a terrified country baby to survive, but hes resilient. Right from the beginning, this gentle little (only 36 lbs) 1-year-old flat coated retriever mix wanted to trust. It took him a while and some hotdogs to even consider coming out of his shell, but hes nearly done a 180. He barely moved and didnt blink, now he plays and cuddles. He needs an experienced, patient, grownups only home in the burbs, and hed be happiest with a fenced yard and a doggy sibling. Intrested in adopting? Please go to www.socialteesnyc.org 

His Foster Mom Says: Heaton has come such a long way since I first began fostering him. When I first picked him up, it took him a long time to decompress and start to get adjusted. He wasnt interested in food, human affection, or really anything for that matter, and he was super skittish at any and all noises. Fast forward 3 months and he is a completely different dog. He loves to run around in a backyard or on the beach, and loves chasing other dogs! He now takes treats from my hands and knows some simple commands. He is also starting to desire human affection and will always be where I am and sitting in a position where he can touch me. He loves playing right when he wakes up with his chew toys, and has such a funny personality, and is the best napper I know. Heaton is such a sweet, gentle soul, and a patient family in the suburbs will be the best fit for him! I believe having another dog will really help him come out of his shell and show him the way.

PLEASE NOTE: This animal is not at the Social Tees office all of our dogs and cats are in foster homes while they wait to find their forever families. :) If youd like to apply to adopt this pet, please complete an adoption application at socialteesnyc.org. Because we are a small team and receive hundreds of applications each week, we are unable to respond to every application and every inquiry email, but we do our best. Please have patience! If your application is approved, you will for sure hear from us. If you have questions, please take a look at the Adoption and Fostering FAQs etc. on our website as all common questions are answered there. Thank you for your understanding and flexibility as we work to save these innocent lives!! 

LEARN MORE ABOUT US: socialteesnyc.org; Instagram via @socialteesnyc; Facebook.com/socialteesanimalrescue

animal.description:
Dora is estimated to be around five years old but don't let her age fool you, she acts more like a two-year-old pup who is living her best life :)  Dora came to us from a breeding farm. From her very first heat cycle as a pup, she was forced to breed and deliver puppies for profit, litter after litter. We can only imagine what her life was like before but she is not looking back now. She craves human companionship and will follow you around to get pets and love. She is so excited to be with you that she jumps up to give kisses. We are helping her to learn to sit and take a treat nicely, she loves positive reinforcement and is learning quickly! She is a sweet girl and is ready to be in a home of her own. She does well seeing other dogs and may be able to live with a laid back male companion. Because of Dora's past neglect, she had to have her bottom two canine teeth removed but that doesn't slow her down one bit and she feels so much better now. If you are interested in learning more about Dora, contact us today!

If you are interested in adopting or fostering this dog, please contact CHAAMP at CHAAMPapplication@gmail.com for an application. You may also complete an application online thru our web site, www.CHAAMP.org

CHAAMP accepts applications ONLY from Maryland, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Virginia, West Virginia, and Washington DC. The information on your application will help CHAAMP determine which of our dogs is a good match for you and your family, based upon your lifestyle, other pets, etc. A home visit is required prior to all adoptions. Many of our dogs are fostered in private homes and cannot be visited until you have been approved for adoption. 

ADOPTION FEES
~Adult dogs, the fee is $275.00  
~Older dogs (eight years old or over) the adoption fee is $100.00 
~Puppies between 6 months and 1 year are $350.00 
~Puppies under 6 months old are $375.00 

All dogs are microchipped, spayed, and neutered and up to date on vaccines. These fees help us cover these costs.  The rates are higher for puppies because they require more visits to the vet and shots. 

CHAAMP IS NOT A SHELTER. We are volunteers over a 7-state area dedicated to helping Malamutes in our rescue area. You can read more about Malamutes and about CHAAMP by visiting www.CHAAMP.org

animal.description:
We hope you consider adopting a homeless dog from our shelter or any other shelter in the Mid South area.  All our animals are tested for heartworms, vaccinated, microchipped and most are sterilized prior to adoption.  For more information on any animal listed available for adoption, please call us at 870-732-7599.

Dog Adoption Application 

Thank you for your interest in adopting a pet from West Memphis Animal Services.  We want to place our animals in permanent responsible homes and at the same time match you with a pet that is suitable for your family and your lifestyle.

Our Dog Adoption fee is $100.00 which includes: Current on all shots, Rabies, Spay or Neuter, and testing for heartworms, current heartworm and flea and tick prevention and microchipped.
 **You must be at least 21 years old to apply for adoption. 

Please cut and paste these questions and your answers into a new e-mail and forward them to us at: wmas@westmemphisar.gov
 **If you can't cut and paste this application, you can email us with just the answers to the questions. 

1. Name:
2. Date of Birth: 
3. Spouse or Co-Applicant:
4. Address/City/State/Zip:
5. What area do you live in? 
6. Home Number:
7. Work Number:
8. Cell Number:
9. Email Address:
10. Occupation:
11. Spouse/Co-Applicant Occupation:
12. Are you a student?
13. Name of Pet You Are Applying For:
14. Why are you interested in this pet? 
15. Do you Own or Rent your home? 
16. Please describe your home environment: (Apartment, House, Condo, Townhouse, Trailer, Mobile Home, Pool) 
17. Do you have a pet door? 
18. Do you have a completely fenced in yard? How tall is your fence? 
19. What type of fence do you have (wood, chain link, etc)? 
20. If you do not have a fence, how do you plan to confine the pet to your yard? 
21. If you rent, do you have the landlord's permission to adopt an animal? 
22. Name of Landlord and phone number: 
23. Is there is a pet deposit or fee required? If so, have you paid it? 
24. Does your job require that you move or travel often? 
25. When traveling what do you do with your pet?
26. Number of adults in household? 
27. Do any children live in or visit your home? What are their ages?
28. Please list the names, ages, and breeds of the pets you currently own:
29. Please list the pets you have had in the past and explain what happened to them.
30. Are your pets vaccinated? 
31. Are your pets on heartworm prevention? If so, what brand?
32. Have your pets been spayed or neutered? 
33. If no, please explain.
34. Who is or was your Vet, including address and phone number: 
35. How many times a day do you feed and what brand food do you feed?
36. Please describe what a typical day and a typical week will be for your new pet. 
37. Where will the dog spend its days? 
38. Where will the dog sleep at night? 
39. How many hours a day will the pet be left alone?
40. Do you plan to allow the dog outdoors? 
41. How long do you plan to keep this pet?
42. What behaviors would you consider unacceptable in your pet?
43. How would you correct these behaviors?
44. What would you do if your dog kept having accidents in the house? 
45. How would you discipline your dog from unwanted behavior? 
46. Have you ever kennel trained a dog before? 
47. Are you prepared for the costs involved in properly caring for a pet (food, treats, toys, grooming, shots, heartworm and flea and tick prevention, litter, etc)?
48. Many breeds are now banned in apartments and by insurance companies. If you are applying for a rottweiler, german shepherd, akita, doberman, pitbull, chow, or other guardian type breed, have you checked with your homeowner's insurance to make sure that you are allowed to own the breed? If you are applying to adopt a rottweiler from us, what insurance company are you with?
49. Is the animal going to be a gift for someone?
50. Are other members of your family aware that you want to adopt an animal?
51. Is anyone in your family allergic to animals?
52. Do you have any health issues that could affect your ability to care for a companion pet? 
53. Have you adopted an animal before? If so, where?
54. How did you hear about us? (petfinder, facebook, friend, etc)
55. Do you understand that if you adopt a pet from us, you are required to return the pet to us if you can no longer keep it?
56. The vet reference is usually all we need as a reference, however in some cases we do need to check other references. Please list 2 references, including name and telephone number in case we need to contact them.
57. We very rarely adopt long distance, if you are out of the area, how would you plan to get the pet? 
58. How would you return the pet to us if the pet didn't work out in your home?
59. Please add any comments you would like to make here that will help us make a good decision for you and for your new companion. 

Thank you for your interest in one of our homeless pets! Your answers will be reviewed and your vet reference will be contacted. We will contact you as quickly as we can, but please remember we deal with a high volume of calls, emails, and applications. 

An incomplete application WILL NOT be processed. Falsification of any of the above information will be grounds for rejection of this application.
